She got her vaccine, she started tasting the medicine first, and then her mouth got watery and started having little chest pains.   She waited the 15 minutes and left, and did tell the pharmacy lady her symptoms.  Her arm was red, and had a headache, but didn't think anything of it.  After 2 weeks she had a red arm, hot, shiny and swollen.  She went back to the store, and had the pharmacy lady look at it who told her she had an allergic reaction, take some Benadryl and go to her doctor.  She took that and went to her doctor as the symptoms did not go away.   She sent her to an allergy specialist.  She did blood work and went to the specialist and still taking the Benadryl.  It was kind of going away, but the rash was warm and he did allergy testing and told her that she had allergies to trees, grasses, etc.   During the time of waiting for the test results of the allergy testing she continued to have the headaches and her mouth started getting dizzy.  She thought maybe it was just allergies.  She was at work cutting hair and almost cut a child as she felt dizzy and fatigued and it gradually came on her.  She had to sit down for a while and that feeling did not go away.  Her boss told her to finish and she was about to cut a child and went to her car, and laid in the car all day as she could not drive home.  She was feeling that it was just some allergies.  Called her husband and went to a store within walking distance, and she was holding onto the basket and feeling dizzy and fatigued and was facetiming her husband and then she felt lost, did not know why she was in the store.  She didn't remember where the car was, and walked around for an hour not knowing what to do or why she was there.  She then sat down to try and get her senses and took something for her headache.  She got to the car and zoned out and tried to drive home and was not able to due to the dizziness and fatigue, but could not remember to drive and telling herself to push the gas and was only going about 5 miles an hour.  She called her husband and told him that she could not drive home, and stayed in the parking lot a little bit longer.  It took her 3 hours to get home, which was normally at 20 minute commute.   She went back to her PCP and told her what happened and told her that she did not feel safe, confused, watery mouth and headache.   She then ordered an MRI to see what was going on.  She then tried to get home again and had another episode and was not able to make it home.  She went to the ER and they ran a lot of tests, CT scan, x-rays and told her that all tests were normal.  He then looked at her and did a neurologic test and told her hat he could not send her home and told her that she did not look fine.  She told him that she did not feel safe, and was not able to function.  She gave him a description of how she felt, and told him that she has short term memory problems, and that if she is driving she does not realize that she is.  She was then admitted to the hospital and did 2 more  CT scans, an MRI, blood work and ended up having a neurologist see her, and told her that all her tests were negative.  It was even hard for her to walk and she had to see a therapist for that, and they put her on some medicine for the dizziness and fatigue.  She was in the hospital for 3 days.    She went back to the doctor on Monday and still having the symptoms, but the medicine did help some.  The doctor saw that she could not walk and fell over.  She called the neurologist again and did another blood tests to see if she had COVID prior to the vaccine and doubled up on the medicine for the dizziness which did help with that but the other symptoms were still there, but she was able to walk but not drive.   She had her go to another neurologist to do an MRI of the brain with contrast of the ear part, and she is to go to the doctor today for those results.  From 2/26/21 until now 5/3/21 she has been taking the medicine to function and be able to walk.  She tried to wean herself off the medicine but she is not able to walk and the fatigue comes back.  She still is not able to drive as the short term memory hits her and she forgets where she is and not able to keep up with the speed of the freeway and driving only 10 miles an hour.     She then called the doctor again as she was still having the episodes, she has not been able to work and was told that she probably had to see a neuropsychologist.   She also was filing out paperwork at one point and got a headache and was not able to fill out the paperwork correctly, and did not remember her 16 year olds information.  She is not able to return to work as the company she was working sold the company and she is not able to cut 2 haircuts a day without breathing hard and used to be able to cut 30 a day.  Her body hurts so bad that it feels like if you touch her skin it?s like she had a full work up.  Her doctor told her that she did not have COVID but her body is reacting as if she did.  She is also used to taking care of special needs and autism kids cutting their hair and is upset that she cannot provide for her family and used to work 7 days a week, 7 hours a day.   She is supposed to go to the neurologist today for the results of her MRI (while talking to me she could not remember why she was supposed to go to that doctor).   She was also having an episode and not able to speak to me, starting babbling.  I told her to take a deep breath and she did collect herself.  They are still trying to determine what is going on and why she is having these side effects which she did not have prior to the vaccine.  The tests results are showing that she is okay, but the doctors know that she is not.
PRIOR_VAX: Flu vaccine, has given her the flu on two occasions.

The sciatic pain increased dramatically after the first injection.  It was so bad that I was practically confined to my bed or chair/couch.  At first, I thought the increase in pain was due to my increasing activity level.  However, another round of steroids had no effect, and all of the other pain management strategies I normally use were ineffective.  It wasn't until the day before my second injection that I ran across information indicating that the inflammation created by the vaccine could cause joint and nerve pain.  When I arrived for the second injection, I asked the medical professional on-site about it.  She said that the vaccine could definitely have caused the severe pain I'd experienced over the last month.  She even suggested that some patients report that the second injection ameliorates negative effects of the first one. A few days after my second injection, the pain levels decreased and recently returned to pre-vaccine levels.
OTHER_MEDS: I take a statin and blood pressure medication.
HISTORY: I've suffered from lower back pain since my early 20's.  It has become progressively worse and last July I injured it further while lifting something heavy.  That resulted in severe sciatic pain that was checked by a steroid pack and rest.  At the time of the vaccine, I was just starting to increase my activity level after about 3 months of low-level activity.

After the vaccine I had pain/soreness in my shoulder for the next two days but I knew that was to be expected from the shot.  After 2 or 3 more days the pain had subsided some but I was still experiencing a good amount of pain in my shoulder.  After 2 weeks or still having pain I scheduled an appointment to see my physician.  My physician prescribed diclofenac and told me to take them for 2 or 3 weeks to see if that would resolve my pain.  After 3 or 4 weeks I was still having pain so my physician referred me to an ortho specialist. At the time I was having trouble with waking up at night due to the pain so he gave me a cortisone shot and scheduled me a meeting with the physical therapist.  Initially, the cortisone shot worked and I no longer had any pain.  At this point the PT told me as long as I wasn't having any pain we didn't need to continue scheduling meetings but if the pain came back to call in and schedule an appointment. Right at the one month mark I began having pain in my shoulder again and scheduled an appointment for PT.  I had 5 PT sessions scheduled over roughly 2 months.  The pain did seem to decrease but an issue I continued to have was doing certain activities caused the pain to come back. On April 29th I had a follow up with my Ortho Dr. and he scheduled a MRI and an EKG.
LAB_DATA: X-Ray, PT Currently have an MRI and EKG scheduled.

Slight headache, couldn't get to sleep but stayed in bed.  Around 3am that night I decided to get up and get some ibuprofen from the kitchen.  By the time I reached the kitchen, I felt woozy, like I had stood up too soon.  Stopped for a moment till I felt steady and then continued to walk to the cabinet, I also was going to take a xanax to help me sleep (prior to this I had not taken a xanex for probably 4-6 weeks).  I put the xanax in my mouth, grabbed the bottle of ibuprofen and felt like I should lay back down asap.  Took a few steps and passed out and hit my head on small round table shelf.  When I came to, I realized I had not even swallowed the xanex yet, it was still in my mouth. I'm guessing I wasn't out long but my husband didn't hear me fall so that is unclear.  After I woke up and got back in bed, I realized my head was bleeding some from hitting the table.  It appeared to be a small cut on the back of my head and I did not seek medical attention.  I do intend to go to dr to get checked out for what I am guessing is a mild concussion, I have an appt for tomorrow.  There seem to be 2 areas of impact on my head.  I am assuming the back of my head hit the table shelf (near the floor), which was cracked from my head hitting it, and the other impact is to the right side of my head, which I assume is from the table leg.  I think there is only a cut on the back of my head, and not the right side.

In all my 25+ years of having my menstrual cycle, NEVER once have I been early or was in unexpected. I am very regular - 28-29 days. Typically heavy and lasts 7 days. The first day is always the roughest with cramping but after, it subsides. BUT on May 1, 2021 - my period started and I didn't even notice - it was light.  I will say this though - I feel like whatever was in that vaccine actually was a good thing for my body - I don't know how, but I feel great, even 3 days later. Let's hope it lasts. (As a side note- I was never diagnosed with COVID ALTHOUGH I asked my PCP in Jan 2020 when I wasn't getting better since December 2019 if I had that coronavirus  - she assured me at the time that I did not and it was not here. I was convinced myself that I had COVID in December 2019 because I had traveled. I asked her how that virus could not be here yet when we have international travel- she gave me a response but I still was not convinced. so, perhaps I did - perhaps my symptoms in 2020 were long haul covid symptoms and the vaccine helped me.

I spent the entire day on the couch next to a bucket because if I got up, I was too light headed and nauseated to do anything. It lasted 24 hours or so. By day 3 after the shot, I felt okay other than soreness, a headache, and a big itchy rash at the injection site. About 36 hours after my vaccine, the injection site swelled considerably (nearly baseball sized) and was bright red.  However, since swelling is expected and it resolved in two days, I wasn't terribly concerned. On Day 8, however, I woke up to a considerable amount of itching, redness and swelling (ping pong sized). Throughout the day and into the next, the swelling expanded across the entire width of my bicep, approaching the size of a softball. Sensations ranged from itching to burning (the area was hot to the touch) and pain. The paperwork I received with my vaccine indicated symptoms should resolve within seven days of vaccination and to report any prolonged or worsening symptoms. I don't have a PCP/GP, however, so I didn't have a physician to contact. I considered going to an immediate care clinic for evaluation but was afraid of potential COVID exposure and decided to wait a couple more days to see if things improved. I'm now 11 days after my vaccine and 3 days after symptoms began and can report that the swelling does seem to be flattening out, though it is certainly still there (as is the rash). Since it is certainly better today than it was yesterday, I am hopeful things will continue to improve. All the same, I thought it was worth reporting since it began 8 days after my vaccination. I know of dozens of people who have gotten the vaccine, but only one other person who had a similar reaction. In which case, it felt like an anomaly worth reporting. I can provide photos from the past three days, if needed.
OTHER_MEDS: Vitamin D Drops  Multivitamin Occasional probiotic

Also have several suspected allergies to bandage adhesive, unknown artificial fragrances, dyes, flavors and preservatives (I'm not sure which ones, so I avoid them all). At approximately 4:00 PM the EMS was at the facility,  she could not breath or talk and EMS was called and it got worse in the ride to the ER.   She had a severe  headache to the point that somebody grabbed her around the throat and her eyes were popping out of her head.  She had chest pains, and given nitro for that, and had trouble breathing.  She had no voice.  The attempted to give her aspirin in applesauce.  Her temp was taken and it was 97, by the time she was admitted it was elevated.  In the car, EMS was trying to get her veins and 11 attempts were made and she was bruised.   She has waited a year and a half for surgery as she needs right knee replacement, and has spine, joint issues and was not able to move due to extreme weakness.  She was given Epinephrine in her leg and it did not do anything.  She was admitted to the hospital and was there a couple of days until she was able to help her walk.  She had no anxiety and had anger over the nursing staff, attending physician and the way she was treated.  She is a licensed CNA and has worked in 3 hospitals and has a grievance due to the lack of care that she received while in the hospital.  The ER nurses were good, but going to the 6th floor was another issue.     Her Dr. on Saturday ordered a swallow test as they could not determine why she had no voice and could not swallow.  It was done and she was still having difficulty getting food down, but it was slow and did go down.  Since he has been back at ALF she is now better, able to walk, talk and go about her life.   While in the hospital she was having a hard time getting her medications, and was given a breathing treatment in the ER, and was still having problems on the floor and was having problems with them getting her medications so that she could breath.  She finally got their attention and told her that she was not okay with her and the lack of the nursing staff care.   She fought to get her Flonase, and by the time she was ready to leave on Saturday she had been given one treatment of Symbicort.    She did have blood tests done to the point that it was excessive, but she had veins that were blowing and there was no access points.  On Friday she refused them as she had been stuck 11 times.  On Saturday morning they came to get more blood and she refused on Saturday evening when she was being discharged, and she was prescribed a multivitamin to take, which she has never taken one before.    She has no heart issues and no chest pains but was discharged home with nitroglycerin.   She states that she will not be getting the 2nd vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 9 hours later began feeling a general "ick" like when coming down with something, then moderate headache and body aches, especially my back. This lasted less than 2 days.  Other things, mostly starting 5 or 6 days later and some cropping up as late as 4/11.    Random itchy red rashes on each shoulder and back of upper arm that would go away within an hour or 2.   Itching and possibly bumps on buttocks and thighs.  Intensely itching palms for a little while on 2 or 3 different days.  Sudden appearance of a 4 x 4 inch patch of 15-20 bumps of various sizes in the crook of my left elbow (injection arm) with bright red skin. These looked similar to mosquito bites or blisters but didn't itch. It completely disappeared without a trace within an hour.    Tingling tongue followed by tongue swelling on 4/6/21.  I had eaten my bran flakes with some rice pudding a little bit before this, both of which I'd eaten every day for the past week or so and had had several times in the past. On the advice of my doctor's nurse, my husband drove me to an urgent care center. By the time we got there, probably 1.5 hours after this started, the swelling was some better. The nurse practitioner that I saw prescribed an antihistamine and 3 days of one 20 mg prednisone pill a day. I've never had a tingling or swelling tongue before in my life. I took only a half of one prednisone on 4/6, no Allegra.  On 4/7 the random itchy red rashes mostly on arms/shoulders happened once or twice and disappeared fairly quickly, but my upper lip swelled. I could feel it happening as I sat in my recliner in the morning. I hadn't had anything to eat yet. The doctor advised I take my Allegra and prednisone I received at urgent care on 4/6, so I did. The lip swelling gradually went down over a few days, but it still feels irritated on the inside of the lip as of 4/11.   Diarrhea beginning around 1:30 a.m. 4/8. Lasted about 3 days. I only very very rarely have diarrhea.  Mild sore throat starting Friday 4/10. Better by Saturday. Sore throats are so rare for me that I can't remember the last one, possibly several years ago.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received my second vaccination shot of Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine EUA around 9am on Friday April 30th. I was able to work throughout the day and then drove to see family in the afternoon, arriving around 5pm. Within an hour of arriving I began to feel a fever that continued to increase in severity. At various times throughout the evening I was laid up on the couch shivering and shaking without much control. I immediately took two ibuprofen pills and was able to eventually find a thermometer which read 102.7 degrees body temperature. My fever persisted through much of the night and partially broke around 4am. Still, the next day (Saturday 5/1) I still had a 101 degree fever and experienced aches and pains (presumably from the fever). As late as Sunday 5/2 I still had a fever of 100.1 but was feeling better. I did experience some minor and brief tightness in my chest on Sunday morning but it subsided quickly. Now 5/3 I feel better but still a bit hungover from the fever, shaking and lack of sleep.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I initially spoke to the patient when she came to the vaccination clinic to receive her second dose of Moderna vaccine on 4/15/21. The patient explained to me that she had not been doing well since she received her first dose of vaccine.  Her first dose was 3/18/21, administered on the right side.  After the first dose she had some rash, but also had more significant issues involving her joints on the side of her first injection.  I could see that she was having difficulty with her right wrist and hand.  She also said that she was having trouble with her knee.  I advised her at that time to take some time to see if those issue resolved and to speak to her provider before getting the second dose.  We agreed that she would let me know what the doctor told her. I received a follow-up phone call the week of 4/19/21.  She told me that her doctor advised her not to get the second dose because the rash was indicative of an allergic reaction.  Her doctor also told her that when she was vaccinated, the vaccinator likely hit a nerve and that is what is causing her joint issues. I heard from the patient again on 4/28/21.  She told me that she has started to see a neurologist for the issues that she is having.  She said that she was told that her problems were a result of the way the vaccine was administered and that the needle was ?way too high.?  She also mentioned that her daughter is a nurse and explained that there is a right place to inject in the arm.  She said that her wrist is horrible and that she can?t use her right hand.  Her knee and joints on the right side are bad, but the worst is her wrist and hand.

Five minutes after vaccination, mother noticed the patient was pale on forehead, followed by "overall paleness" a minute later. Patient reports feeling slightly light-headed five minutes post-vaccination. He said he also felt warm and slightly sweaty. Eight minutes post-vaccination, his mother said his earlobe "lost color". The patient reported feeling cool and sweaty around this time and still light-headed. 19 minutes post vaccination (at 10:06 AM), patient informed me of how he was feeling, and I checked his blood pressure. It was 93/47, with a pulse of 55. He felt very hot to the touch, but his temp was 96.8 degrees. He brought a water bottle to sip water as needed, and he was given a cool cloth for his neck/forehead. At 10:10 AM, patient reported feeling weak and didn't want to talk. At 10:13 AM (~25 min post vaccination), patient reported feeling a "bit better", and his BP was 104/57 (checked by other RPh). 34 minutes post-vaccination he reported feeling much better and was much less light-headed/able to talk. At 10:26 AM (~39 min post-vaccination), BP was 137/75, and his pulse was 60. 42 minutes post-vaccination, he said he was "mostly back to normal; ~90%". Then, 46 minutes post-vaccination, he said he was 95% better, and he said he was "good to go" 51 minutes post-vaccination.
ALLERGIES: Patient reports having a "mild seizure" after pertussis vaccine as a child, as well as sensitivity to cephalosporins, alcohol, and dairy (diarrhea reported with all three).

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Shingles. Within 24 hours the right side of my mouth (tongue, gums, palate but not down the throat) was blistered. This resolved within about 4 days. Within 4 days my upper back, primarily the right side, had large single blisters. That resolved in another few days. Within a week my face, neck, and even scalp were covered in blisters and rashes - primarily on the right side and center. My hands were also blistered though not as severely. Because SHINGLES HAS NOT BEEN PUBLICIZED AS A POTENTIAL SIDE EFFECT (SHAME ON CDC), I had no clue what was going on. I used salt-water rinses for the mouth blisters, nothing on the back, and started with Benadryl and Caladryl for the rest. One April 21, the day my 2nd vaccine was due and it was clear something very wrong was going on, I went to an urgent care center and received a steroid shot, 7-day steroid pack, and topical steroid cream. The blisters and rash continued. I saw my general practitioner April 26. He said to continue the topical cream and wouldn't prescribe more steroids at that time. He also said I was past the time when the shingles anti-viral would be effective.  I STILL have blisters, though they are subsiding. NO ONE CAN TELL ME IF I SHOULD GET THE 2ND SHOT, WHEN I SHOULD GET IT, AND WHAT TO EXPECT. I hope to get it, but this is scary.

On the second week (Apr 19 to Apr 23, 2021) have frequent muscle pain, muscle on calf becomes stiff and harden and occur more frequent. It alternates between right calf and right forearm. I also often have tingling on fingertips, numbness on hand and feeling fuzzy on arm, legs. Symptoms comes and goes but get worse if have short walk. Foot and back of the knee on right leg cramp and more stiffness and more pain. On May 2, I woke up with numbness on my right foot and discover red spot on the instep. This prompt me to go to Urgent care. Since numbness and feeling of fuzzy along arms and legs but at the urgent care could not diagnose since they don't have tools to run the test so they advise if it bothers me, I should go to the ER. I worry about high cost of ER so I went home and plan to go see family doctor on Monday but just 5 minutes away from urgent care, I have trouble saying out the word that I want to say. It just doesn't come out although I try to form a word. At that point I more concern if I would have stroke so I ask my husband to turn around to go to Emergency Room. While waiting to be treated, numbness occurs more on feet and under of the forearms, Doctor run blood test, order ultrasounds, MRI scan on the head and EKG. All result came back normal but numbness and headache still persistent. I was discharge in the evening but still have no idea what cause it. The discharge paper indicate that it is "Paresthesia" and I believe Janssen vaccine is the cause for all the symptoms that I have. I still have numbness on feet and leg stiffness still occur even sit down for less than 5 minutes. Should the staff administered the Moderna type that I have signed up for. I believe this side effect won't happen to me. I signed up for Moderna but after check in, the staff show a note "L@837" to the fire fighter. I don't know what it means but heard their conversation that "We don't do that today" then after vaccine was administered, I found out that it is Janssen that I have not signed up for.

Approximately ten hours after injection, woke up with constant chills, fever of 100.1, body aches, stuffed nose (had to breathe out of mouth), and headache. Acetaminophen helped slightly. For the next 12 hours fever stayed between 101 and 102 despite continuing to take acetaminophen, and headache also didn't improve. At 6:15 pm that day (~29 hours post-shot) fever was 103.2, headache was very strong (with light sensitivity). Since acetaminophen hadn't been helping, switched to ibuprofen. About an hour later, the fever finally began to go down and was gone by 10 pm that night. The next day, no fever and minimal headache, but was very weak and lightheaded. At about 51 hours after the shot, symptoms were all gone.

Two  days after my second shot, I started experiencing really bad joint pain, a headache, a fever and what felt like my veins were on fire. I received the shot on Wednesday and was fine on Thursday and Friday morning, but I had taken Tylenol and Airborne all day Wednesday Thursday and Friday morning in the hopes of reducing symptoms. The headache started on Friday afternoon. The other symptoms on Saturday morning and lasted on and off all weekend. It went a way for a bit, but then came back. The weather was very rainy, so I wrote it off as mild arthritis pain, but it persisted and kept getting worse. But, we had a rainy March and April. It is now May and the pain continues. Sometimes in my joints. Sometimes not. Across the back of my right hand is the worst and almost constant. On and off, I get the headaches, pains in my joints or muscles, or just across my thigh, or my calf. None of this happened before the shot, so I am thinking it may be elated.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: First I noticed that my eyes were very sensitive to light, I was also feeling light headed and dizzy on my walk back to the car. (about 30 minutes after injection). I had someone else drive because I felt like I could not drive in my condition. On the ride home, about 40 minutes after injection, I began to have an increased heart rate and had a hard time swallowing. It was also slightly difficult to breathe. I felt like my head was cloudy and I had a hard time concentrating. I felt like my brain was responding about a half a second slower to what I saw. Like if I wanted to turn my head, I would think try to turn my head and my body would react a second later. When I got home, about 1 hour after the injection, my girlfriend told me my hands were freezing cold. I was also having a hard time walking in straight because I was so dizzy. I was still having some minor trouble breathing and swallowing. It was difficult to drink water. After about 2 hours my breathing returned to normal. My mind was cloudy all day, I felt like I was drunk.  On the second day, I woke up with an intense headache. It lasted for 3 days. My arm started to hurt on the second day as well, no pain at all the first day. My head was still cloudy and I had difficulty trying to recall memories or answer questions. By the third day this was basically gone. I was extremely tired for three days total. My mind remain cloudy for about a week.
Swollen node developed on outside of left hip.  Sensitive to touch but not painful.  Approximately the size of a golf ball. Hard to the touch.

Nasal Congestion  -consider use of OTC medications such as DayQuil/NyQuil, Robitussin or Delsym for cough  - OTC nasal spray and decongestants may provide temporary relief. If you have hypertension, diabetes, thyroid disease, or are pregnant you should avoid using these products. - A mix of 1/2 honey and 1/2 lemon juice can be used to soothe the throat and help loosen thick mucus in the throat or use warm salt water gargles.  Use of hard candy, or throat lozenges for sore throat or cough (sugar free if Diabetic) -Steam inhalation by standing in a hot shower or sitting in the bathroom when hot shower is running helps with nasal discomfort. Vaporizers and humidifiers are not recommended due to the risk of burns, bacterial growth in improperly cleaned equipment, and mold formation in the home  -Saline nose drops help loosen secretions. Commercial or homemade may be used (1/4 tsp. salt dissolved in 8 ounces warm water distilled or boiled water, discard solution after 48-72 hours)  -Consume extra fluids, maintain a nutritious diet, get adequate rest  -Take Tylenol as needed for pain and/or fever.

Male patient (date of birth: 02/05/1962) received the 1st COVID Vaccine (Pfizer, Lot #: ER8731 and expiration date: 08/2021) on 04/09/2021 at 12:45PM. Client returned to the vaccine site on 04/30/2021, for his second dose. Client was checked in by the ancillary staff and then sat down with a nurse vaccinator at one of the vaccination stations. As the vaccinator screened the client, some medical concerns came up so the vaccinator went over to the lead nurse for a consult. Nurse received a brief report from the vaccinator, and then walked over to the vaccination station to talk to the client. The client explained to Nurse that he received his first dose on his left arm and about 2 days later, he developed "numbness and tingling" in that same arm and it has not resolved. As Nurse asked further questions, she discovered that the client also started to develop that same sensation, of numbness and tingling, in his right hand. The client described that it is painful, if poked in those areas. Nurse also asked if this feeling radiates anywhere else and the client explained that, if he sits for a prolonged period of time, the numbness and tingling will develop in both of his lower extremities and he needs to get up and walk around. Client reported that it is not painful in a way that he can rate it on a pain scale of zero to ten, but he did describe it as being "abnormal for him" and "not comfortable." Client denied any known drug allergies as well as denied any past medical history. He stated he had his left index finger amputated "years ago, but that is it." Nurse explained to the client that there are some concerns regarding the new onset of symptoms after receiving the vaccine and that she would like to get a medical consult before deciding how to proceed with the second dose. Client agreed. Nurse sent a text message for a medical consult received an answer about 45 minutes later. The medical team recommended waiting to give the second dose until the client is assessed by either a primary care provider or neurologist. They also gave the client the option of receiving the JOHNSON and JOHNSON vaccine 28 days after the first dose, if the client does not wish to receive PFIZER again. Nurse then educated the client on the recommendations. The client expressed to Nurse that he is "very healthy and does not go anywhere," so he does not wish to be seen by a medical provider right now. The client asked questions regarding vaccine efficacy in the first and second doses and Nurse addressed them. The client told Nurse that at this time, he would like to hold off on getting a medical assessment and did not wish to reschedule for a JOHNSON and JOHNSON vaccine. Nurse respectfully acknowledged his decision and educated him on V- safe and how to proceed if he changes his mind later down the road.

Around 2 pm, my upper right arm where the shot was given was sore, but it went away in the evening on 4/30/21. I continued to take Benadryl throughout the day and cromolyn sodium as I have mast cell activation syndrome.   At approx 2:30 am on 5/1/21, I woke up with some abdominal pain or upset, upper body aches, chills, severe chattering of my teeth, and severe pain in my upper right arm where the injection was given, such that, I could barely move my arm upward. This lasted until approximately 6 am or 7 am. Even with a blanket and a heater running beside me, I was still cold and my teeth were severely chattering. At 8 am, I took an extra dose of my hydrocortisone for a total of 10mg. I had upper body aches and a headache most of the morning. It stopped in the afternoon, but the upper body aches and headache returned in the evening.  I continued to take Benadryl, cromolyn sodium, and Tylenol.   On Sunday, 5/2/21, my symptoms were gone, but I still took an extra dose of hydrocortisone for a total of 10mg.   Today, 5/3/21, I was able to reduce it back to 5mg in the morning and my symptoms are still gone.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: By evening the evening of March 25, 2021, the date I received the second dose of the Pfizer vaccine, I was feeling feverish and having chills. I went to bed early and slept little because of my high fever alternating with icy chills. I didn't have any Tylenol on hand. By morning, I decided to take ibuprofen. Fever and chills subsided. Although I was very tired, I was able to maintain my usual daily routine. Close to noon I decided that I felt well enough to go to mass. I sat in the back in case I had to leave early. By the time I walked to the last pew, I was exhausted. I decided just to sit through mass. Once it started, I realized that I was too worn out to make the responses, so I prayed silently in my heart. Shortly I began to feel lightheaded; then felt nauseated. Decided I needed to get home. Left the church and and walked and then stumbled down the corridor toward the door. Quickly I felt I couldn't get enough air through my mask; removed the string from one ear. Legs gave out. Slid to floor to get blood to my brain and give legs a rest. DIdn't seem to help. At last decided to walk to car although I felt I couldn't walk. Managed to get up, got through door to outside, laid on ground for a few minutes to rest. Trying to get to my nearby car, got back to my feet (though unable to actually stand), went about 2-3 feet, collapsed on ground again, unable to move. Some people saw me, called 911, rescue squad came. Loaded me in to take me to hospital. I protested. Did not want to go to hospital. Called neighbor who came to get me. Took me. home. I rested in bed until next day. Have spotty memory of incident . Slowly regained strength over next week or 10 days.
LAB_DATA: Had regularly scheduled cardiology annual exam three weeks after. After tests, doctor said vaccine-related collapse was not due to any heart issues.

Further supporting this diagnosis are the significantly elevated ESR and CRP markers, he is also had imaging which did not show any specific arthritic findings.  Given the timing of the polymyalgia rheumatica developing following his Covid vaccine this may be an adverse effect to the vaccine.  Finally his quick response to prednisone is further evidence of polymyalgia rheumatica.  He does not have any evidence of visual loss, or severe headache to suggest temporal arteritis presents.
LAB_DATA: CMP, ESR, CRP, CBC, Troponin, and lipase

She got her vaccine, and she remembers very clearly that she had mentioned to her husband that whoever was administering the vaccine had given it high up on the arm and did not cover it with a band-aide. For the next couple of days had the usual sore arm. Eventually about 1 to 1/2 weeks after she was taking some anti-inflammatory medication for 3-4 weeks. Once that wore off 2 days later she had severe pain in her left shoulder, and it was out of the ordinary, no trauma to that shoulder, nothing to have caused that pain. She went to take a shower and got dressed and noticed that she had a sore arm within 5-10 minutes had full blown sharp pain. She went to the closest ER and asked her about the vaccine and did not look into that, and took an x-ray and gave her pain medication. She took that and it did not help her much and then saw her physician. When they saw how much pain that she was in and could not move her arm at all and were suspicious for an inflammatory process. She had an MRI that showed a good to moderate amount of fluid in her left arm bursa and that this should be looked into. Her blood work came back as showing that she had some sort of infection going on. She was told to go to an ER immediately so that they could tap the fluid and see what was going on. She went to another ER and then they started investigated and she had a lot of infected shoulder bursa that was isolated to that area and said that it had to be inoculated. Eventually she had to have surgery to get the shoulder bursa cleaned out and found that it was a common bacteria on the skin, and administered by inoculation. She mentioned to her orthopedic that she had the vaccine and no band-aide and that he agreed it was due to that. She was on anti-inflammatories that masked the pain so that's why it took so long to find it. She now has a frozen shoulder, and has a PICC line inserted so she can get antibiotics 3 times a day for a full month and is finishing that course today. The surgery was 4/6/21 and started that a day or two before the surgery.

I called my Dr. on day two, but they didn't think it was the vaccine, and said I should call the health dept.  I did, and they said to call the Doctor.  I decided to wait it out over the weekend, treating the itch with vinegar, and taking some Claritin.  Now (Day 5), the lesions are going away, and nothing itches, but I do still have rough, bumpy, and patchy red lesions.  Hopefully these also go away.  I did finally have two good nights sleep!

SYMPTOM_TEXT: client approached the EMT station complaining of neck pain. Client was alert and tracking with her eyes and appeared to be in mild discomfort. Client had a chief complaint of left side, anterior neck pain. Client stated that approximately five minutes into the observation, she began to experience neck pain and denied any history of severe injury or surgery to the site. This is the client's first dose of the Pfizer vaccine. Client states that she has a secondary history of seizures for which she takes lamotrigine for daily. Client stated she was allergic to ibuprofen. Assessment revealed 8/10 pain on the anterior of the left side of the client's neck that was non radiating. She described the pain as a "pinch and burn" that began abruptly. Client was negative for swelling, hives, discoloration, shortness of breath or other signs of anaphylaxis. Client's vaccine was on the left deltoid and negative for pain upon palpation and intact. Client's airway, breathing and circulation were intact. Client was alert and oriented to person, place, date and event. Client's initial vitals at 1240 were blood pressure 108/74, pulse 86, respirations 16, 99% O2 saturation, Breathing at 16, Eyes equal and reactive to light, Lung sounds clear bilaterally, and skins were normal throughout her body. Client denied this complaint resembling any type of aura for her seizures. Client agreed to stay for the additional 30-minute observation. Water was given. Vitals were taken every 5mins for 30mins. Patient felt better and pain went down to 3/10. Patient refused to stay for the remaining of observation and emergency precautions were given and recommended to follow up with PCP and register for Vsafe. She left site in no distress.

This was my 2nd dose. DAY 1 8:45 am Similar to the first shot almost immediately my tongue went numb and swelled up a bit. DIFFERENT from my first dose, on Day 1 the 2nd dose my upper lip also swelled up and went numb. The gums around my top teeth also went numb. There was an usual taste in my mouth as well. The numbness etc. subsided after a few hours. Then at 10pm my tongue and upper lip swelled and went numb all over again. This lasted 20min or so. This intermittent swelling and numbing continued off and on for the first 10 days after the shot. At no point did I need to use the EpiPen. Was not life threatening. Just weird feeling.   Also on day 2 only I ran a low grade fever and had a mild case of vertigo [which I had never experienced in my life before]. That went away after that day but the numbness and swelling continued intermittently for 10 days. Some days it wouldn't happen then the next day it would. Seemed random.  Worth noting though I had an allergic reaction to both doses, I have never in my life had an allergic reaction to any vaccine prior.

Had vaccine shot on April 30, 2021 at 2:55 pm, woke up at 3AM on May 1st, sweating, headache and nauseous.  got out of bed at 7 and could barely stand up by whole body ached and severe pain in my lower back.  My skin hurt to have anything touching it.  About 10am and threw up and starting having diarrhea which went on for over an hour.  I could not sleep of get comfortable.  I tool Tylenol to help with pain but it did nothing.  I drank lots of fluids and laid around all day.  I could not sleep that night, tossed and turned all  night from the ache and pain in my body.  morning of May 2nd, I got up showered and went for a walk around the block.  By the time I got back I was exhausted and my body was still very sore.  I went back to bed.  I had no idea I would experience such side effects as these are not well known.  Night of May 2nd I slept good, today May 3rd, I feel much better but my lower back is still very sore.  Scary as at one point I thought me and my husband might have to go to ER, my husband had a fever of 100.1 and could not get out of bed for 2 days.   Today I have not fully recovered but am functioning.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is a 79 y.o. female with a history of CAD, COPD, chronic CHF, DM2, HTN who presented to hospital 4/14/2021 with chest pain, upper abdominal pain and ongoing melena.    1. Melena: Ongoing for 6 weeks per patient. Underwent colonoscopy 4/7/21 with polypectomy, no inflammation or bleeding. CT A/P 4/14/21 with mild esophagitis, mild colitis, no other acute finding. IV PPI BID. GI followed, pt is s/p EGD 4/15/21 with normal esophagus, large hiatal hernia with multiple Cameron ulcers and erosive gastropathy with no stigmata of recent bleeding. Biopsied. H&H stable at discharge. Avoid NSAIDs. Discharged on PPI  2. Colitis: Mild on CT A/P. Stool PCR discontinued as diarrhea resolved. Patient is s/p cipro/flagyl in ED. Transitioned to Unasyn with end date 4/15/21.  3. Acute Blood Loss Anemia: Baseline Hgb ~ 12-14. Down to 5.8 on admit in setting of GI bleed. Transfused 1 unit pRBC 4/14/21. Trend H/H Q6H. Transfuse for Hgb < 8 given cardiac diease. Iron studies with evidence of iron deficiency. s/p IV iron. H&H stable at discharge 4. AKI: Baseline creat ~ 0.7-0.8. Elevated to 1.35 in the setting of bleeding/anemia. Held ACEi and diuretic. She did receive IV contrast. Colloid resuscitation with blood transfusion. Resolved 5. Chest Pain w/ Elevated Troponin: Troponin T 16 on admit in setting of severe anemia and poor clearance with AKI. ECG non acute on admit. CT PA negative 4/14/21. Suspect demand ischemia. Negative delta troponin. No further workup.  6. Hx COVID 19: Positive testing 12/2020. Repeat testing ordered in ED 4/14/21 and remains positive. She desaturated only after receiving IV fentanyl in ED. Asymptomatic, CT chest 4/14/21 without GGO. Given > 90 day, patient remain in isolation per OhioHealth Policy.  7. CAD: LHC 9/28 with diffuse disease DES to OM1 and BMS to Circ/OM1. Held ASA/Plavix on admit due to GIB, resumed at discharge. Continued home statin, imdur, BB.  8. Chronic HFrEF: due to ischemic cardiomyopathy. LV 45% on LHC. Continued BB, Imdur. ACEi and Maxzide held initially with GIB and hypotension. PCP follow up 9. HTN: Soft BP on 4/15/21. Continued Imdur and BB with hold parameters. Norvasc, Maxzide, and ACEi discontinued at discharge. Follow up with PCP   10. IDDM2: A1c 7.8% on 3/2021. Continued home regimen.  11. Essential tremor: Follows with Dr. (Neurology). Continued home Propranolol.  12. Pulmonary Nodule: Ct chest 4/14/21 with 6mm pulmonary nodule, repeat in 6-12 moths.
LAB_DATA: 4/14/21 NP swab for SARS-CoV-2 positive WBC 17,8, Hgb 5.8, Hct 21.3, Plt 532

I used Aleve and Tylenol for fever, drank Pepto to attempt calming stomach, and used ice packs on my feet and a heating pad on stomach to try and decrease the cramping. On April 12, shortly after I got my second Pfizer shot, I started my period. It was very early by several weeks, and only a week since my previous period ended, which is why I made note of it and have kept a record.  For the first week it was fairly light and mostly spotting. After a week, it progressed and became more like a normal period in terms of the amount of blood I was seeing. By April 23rd I started noticing a lot more blood clots in my period than usual--ordinarily I'll see one or two each time I get my period, but there were about five days in a row when I noticed multiple blood clots. The clots stopped around April 28th, but as of today (May 3rd) my period is still ongoing, making it exactly three weeks long, and more unless it suddenly stops today.  For the most part the blood has been red and I haven't noticed any other unusual discharge. I have noticed the past few days that the blood is more brown, like old blood.  I have not experienced bad cramps or stomach upset during this very long period--I had the same level of menstrual cramping/stomach upset that I am accustomed to over the first couple of days, but nothing since then. I have felt bloated and tired the entire time, however. I have also experienced a really low mood for these few weeks, though I can't be certain if this is worse than I usually experience on my period, because it may just be because it's lasting so long that it feels worse.
HISTORY: Fibromyalgia (very mild case, only occasional pain/exhaustion flare ups)

Hi, my name is, I'm a RN and am submitting this report about my grandpa.  I took him into the VA to get his second covid vaccine on 2/17/21.   At that time my grandp lived semi-independently in a house between my parents and my uncle .  He didn't get out very much but with some help of grocery shopping and organizing his medication he was still able to live alone and function well independently.  My mother reported to me on 2/18/21 that my grandpa was confused, weak and tired.  My grandpa has never had any signs of dementia.  At this time he developed a delerium that waxed and waned.  He complained of headache, no appetite and extreme weakness.  On 2/23/21 he fell down in his house and we decided to move him into my uncles spare bedroom to keep better eyes on him.  The delerium persisted and on 3/5 he was taken to Hospital for a workup for his delerium and weakness.  There he saw Dr. an internal medicine doctor at hospital.  The workup showed an elevated BNP (probably baseline but I'd have to look at previous lab results) but nothing further.  We opted not to do further imaging and instead take him home.  It became obvious to me that this was the end of his life and so I requested a hospice referral from Dr. My grandpa died on 3/24/21.

"44 yo woman with COVID infection in December, DM2, HTN, FSGS, obesity, sleep apnea, amenorrhea, and h/o allergy to shellfish and iodine with anaphylaxis.  After her first dose of the vaccine she immediately noticed flushing of her face and later that day noticed that she had a rash on her face.  She did not report this reaction prior to the second dose of vaccine, but she did tell her vaccinator afterwards and so she was escorted to the treatment area for observation immediately after.  Within a few minutes she was complaining of trouble breathing due to a sense of constriction and congestion in her throat, no wheezing, no itching.  She began to notice that her voice sounded different in that it was more raspy.  She visibly appeared to be working hard at breathing, although it was difficult to discern to what degree this symptom was due to her obesity.  Her O2 sat was 98-100% throughout and her BP and pulse were stable, if slightly hypertensive.  Her lung exam was CTAB. Due to the progression of her symptoms to voice changes, she was immediately administered an EPI-pen.  Within a moment or two, she noted relief in her throat constriction and her voice returned to normal.  She was observed to have decreased work of breathing and appeared much more comfortable.  She was then given 50 mg of benadryl orally.   She noted a racing heartbeat with the EPI-pen but no chest pain.   She agreed to be monitored for a return of symptoms for an extended period of time and she was informed that she would need someone to drive her home today and stay with her.   At 1515 pm she continued to be free of symptoms and at that time her vital signs were 138/83, 90, 100% on RA.  Her family came to pick her up and she was instructed to call 911 if symptoms return."

1. Immediately upon injection, my tongue started to go numb, and it was numb/tingly within 10 seconds.  2. Over the 15 minutes I sat and waited, the sensation spread to much of my mouth and started to go down into my throat. I did not feel like anything was swelling per se, but definitely numb.  3. At 15 mins, it still seemed to be progressing, so I notified staff and went back to the first aid area. I was monitored and we waited to see what would happen. The numbness went a good way down my throat.  4. When I had some water, I noted that I was able to swallow fine but could barely feel the water going down. I also noted the tingling sensation had spread to the lower part of my face (that had been covered by my mask), though my face was not completely numb -- it felt like when local anesthetic is wearing off.  5. I stayed for a while longer, was evaluated by a doctor, and was eventually released. The numbness largely subsided by 4-5 hours after injection.   6. Notably, I have never had any sort of reaction to a vaccine before. 7. Concerned at a stronger such reaction to the second injection, an immunologist suggested I skip it and instead.

Previously healthy 16 year old young man presenting with chest pain admitted for myopericarditis.   He was in his usual state of good health until 2 days ago when he experienced fever, chills and myalgias after receiving his 2nd dose of COVID pfizer vaccine. He improved until 5/2 when he developed a crushing, non-radiating, substernal chest pain which was waxing and waning in nature without specific alleviating factors. He had shortness of breath, but no palpitation, dizziness, or changes in pain on exertion vs rest. Family activated EMS who gave 325 mg of aspirin en route to the ED.   In the ED, he was afebrile and hemodynamically stable. He was mildly diaphoretic, but otherwise, unremarkable on physical exam. STAT EKG showed ST elevations in V5 and V6 and ST depressions in V1 and V2 as well as PR depressions, which persisted on repeated EKG. Given concern for myopericarditis, they ordered labs including CBC, CMP, troponin and inflammatory markers which were only remarkable for troponin of 1.94 and CRP 3.5. Chest x-ray was normal.    Cardiology was consulted and they recommended transthoracic echo which is pending. Cards also recommended starting Ibuprofen 600 mg q8 hrs and admission to cards for further management.
LAB_DATA: EKG, ECHO, Cardiac MRI, CXR, Labs (CBC, CMP, Trop, Inflam markers,

I went to bed around 10pm feeling very cold an shivering. I was able to fall asleep, but then I woke up at 2am feeling very thirsty and experiencing intense nausea. I got out of bed to get some water. When I exited the room the nausea intensified so I knelt on the floor to wait until it passed. It didn't really pass so I stood up to try and get back to the bed. After a few steps I blacked out and fell to the floor. I was only unconscious for a few seconds, as confirmed by my wife who heard me fall. When I came to, I was lying face down and still experiencing intense nausea. I was also very hot and sweating, and very thirsty. I laid with my eyes closed an breathing very heavily to suppress the urge to vomit for a minute or two. When the urge to vomit began to subside I took a few sips of water while still lying on the ground. After another minute or two I was able to get up and get back into bed. The extreme nausea subsided after a few more minutes and I was able to drink more water. I went back to sleep after that. I woke up in the morning around 7am. I felt a little "off" for most of the day: slightly weak, a mild headache, with some difficulty focusing. But since then I have felt normal.   I didn't seek medical attention or take any medication. I have experienced Vasovagel Syncope as a child so I expect that I am more susceptible to fainting like in this case.

Patient has a history of getting vaccinations from us over the years never with any issues. The only allergy he has history of is contrast dye (anaphylaxis). Patient stated he was feeling well today, no symptoms. Patient was upset and worked up about his insurance stating he has no coverage right now. Patient was administered his vaccine at approximately 12:45p. At about 12:53p patient started saying he was feeling nauseous and felt like he was going to throw up. We handed him a bag. He stood up and started to walk away. We were able to get him to sit down and stay in the pharmacy area, he refused to lie down. Patient's wife asked for water for him, but we told her we were unable to give him water. He was burping and dry heaving but not actually throwing up. This went on for about 5 minutes. I measured his blood pressure at 12:58p and it was 142/76, pulse 73. He was offered ice pack, and to lie down once again. All of which was refused. He verified he was not having any swelling of his face, lips tongue, throat, no difficultly breathing. We also called for store management to come to pharmacy. He and wife stated that he is on an antibiotic for diverticulitis which causes him to do this frequently/daily where he burps up air and dry heaves, but because he hadn't eaten today he was not actually throwing up. Also because of his history of gastric bypass he usually is unable to throw up because there's nothing in his stomach. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient, 10/31/44 was admitted Sunday night for confusion, weakness, and a fall at home. Patient had his Covid-19 vaccine here on 4/9 through the clinic. Per patient?s step-grandson (which is the most involved family member) patient had his first vaccine on March 4th at our clinic. On March 6th patient became extremely weak and step-grandson went to check on him and was unable to get into the house because patient was too weak to get off the couch. A window AC unit had to be removed for step-grandson to get access to patient. They did not seek medical attention at that time and patient improved within a few days back to baseline. Family was unaware that he was getting the second covid shot on 4/9. Patient was seen in grocery store the evening of 4/9 but family was unable to get ahold of patient on Saturday 4/10 and on Sunday (4/11) step-grandson went to his home and found patient on the floor. Patient has been a poor historian but states that he became weak and fell out of a chair. We think he may have been laying on his right side for about 36 hours at home. Patient was found to have blisters on his right forearm and right chest, liver enzymes were elevated on labs and he had dehydration. Patient has also had hallucinations and confusion but everything seems to be slowly improving with supportive care. He is still incontinent which is very unusual for him per family. He was negative for rhabdomyolysis, stroke, C-spine injury, negative for hepatitis, urine drug screen was negative. We are continuing to provide wound care for his blisters and PT/OT. Just a strange case.
Outcome: positive PCR COVID test.
LAB_DATA: COVID PCR nasopharyngeal swab returned positive.

At about 3 hours post injection I began getting chills. I assumed that was a normal side effect but there was no fever. It was a weird sensation like I was getting goosebumps, and 1 day after the injection, they seemed to have more of a rhythm, again without fever. 48 hours after the injection I realized it was now isolated only to the left side of my face. At roughly 51 hours post injection, the left side of my face was tingling with regularity and then began to go numb. The feeling is like that of novacaine  wearing off after a dentist visit. There was no swelling observed but it felt like my lips and inside my mouth were swollen, on the left side. The left side of my face continued to get more & more numb, like a cold sensation and tingling in my lips and cheeks. I went to the urgent care at 55 hours post injection. My BP, temp, and pulse were normal. They did some neurological tests and all were normal. They advised me to go to the ER for a CT scan if it got worse. I went home, monitored it, and by Friday morning, 72 hours post injection my face was no longer numb. There is some residual tingling but it is intermittent and not pronounced.
LAB_DATA: I went back to see a different doctor on Saturday because I also had a slight rash on the left side of torso. The doctor ruled out anything more than contact dermatitis. They drew blood for a routine physical and those results should be back soon. Also checked for anemia (none) and took a urine sample. My BP was low when at the appointment but I felt fine. The practitioner explained they believe the facial numbness to be related to the vaccine but the fact that it was subsiding was a sign that it wasn't something different or worse.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 1-2 days following 2nd Moderna vaccination, patient developed decreased appetite, nausea, fatigue, headache, and abdominal pain. These symptoms progressed and she came for admission on 4/15/21.  She had fevers of unknown origin despite very comprehensive workup. She also was found to have autoimmune hemolytic anemia (COOMBS Test+) requiring blood transfusion. Because she was having headaches, we obtained MRI brain which showed several small punctate strokes. Distribution possibly was scattered. A thorough workup to exclude Endocarditis was performed including transesophageal which all resulted negative. Her fever curve worsened as did her hemolysis until she needed blood transfusions. A CT Scan of Chest/abdomen/pelvis revealed lymphadenopathy of neck and chest up 1.7cm. Biopsy was performed which showed epithelioid granulomas. Stain for infection was negative. She received broad spectrum empiric antibiotics with seemingly no response. Her fevers seemed to start to decrease on 4/24/21 in PM. Once patient had TEE and Biopsy completed, she was started on Corticosteroids on 4/25/21.  This resulted in rapid improvement in fevers, inflammatory markers, and reduction in hemolysis. Symptoms rapidly improved. She was monitored for several more days and then discharged on 5/1/21.

Pt scheduled appointment for and received correct J&J Covid Vaccine that was requested.  There were no issues with processing nor provision. PT advised RPH that he had a problem with needles and experienced low blood pressure every time he was vaccinated or had blood drawn in the past but had done better the last time and did not want to miss out on getting the vaccine.  RPH was prepared and patient was cared for properly.  Pt arrived at 1244 hrs and was provided vaccine at 1247 hours. Patient was fine for about 1 minute and then reported he was having trouble.  Pt remained seated in booth in chair with room to get to floor if needed.  RPH remained with patient, brought his significant other into the booth to help calm the patient as he was alert and orientated and continued to improve while removed mask and fanned with papers (pt stated the fanning was helping).  Pt was improving slowly and moving/trying different positions as he felt he was improving.  At approx 1325 hrs pt knew he needed to lie down and moved himself to floor with the assistance of his significant other and associate (did not fall nor did head impact the floor at any time).  Code White was called.  PT remained alert and orientated and was talking and stated that this was really helping.  Code Team arrived and pt was continuously monitored until he gradually returned to his feet and was able to leave under his own power.  Pt refused medical attention and refused Ambulance - never lost consciousness so no EMT was called.  Pt's significant other was able to drive them home.  Event concluded at approximate 1345hrs.
OTHER_MEDS: None that pharmacist was made aware of.
CUR_ILL: None that pt made us aware of
HISTORY: Pt was aware that he had "low blood pressure" events when exposed to needles.  This had happened to him with each exposure but had gotten better over the last several years.  As such extra precautions were taken incase a vasovagal event occurred.

Got injected, didn?t hurt much. Was told to wait 15 minutes in case of reaction. They walked away and left me sitting in a chair in a public space with everyone else who was waiting. I texted my wife to check in, when I started tearing up and crying for no real reason, then started feeling nauseous so I closed my eyes.   Suddenly I felt like I had been given a shot of adrenaline out of nowhere so I?m just trying to figure out if it?s nerves or a physiological response to something. I?m trying to control my breathing but having a hard time breathing.   Then the fever hit. The most intense flash of heat. I was hyperventilating. I couldn?t open my eyes or move or make a sound, I could just sit there struggling to breathe. My phone was in my hand and I couldn?t lift it. I just simply didn?t have the strength or energy to move.   At some point I legit thought I was about to die. I managed to angle my wrist so I could check my heart rate with my watch. It was 47bpm.   I was fading away but I made myself get control of my breathing and forced myself to take long deep slow breaths. It hurt, and I felt like passing out, but I kept doing it.   Fever turned into chills and then I soaked through my jeans and T-shirt in under a minute. I was finally thinking clearly and breathing and getting oxygen. Everyone else near me was fine.   Nobody checked on me the entire time including the 3 people who sat there and watched me suffer through this.  I told the pharmacist about my reaction and asked if it was normal and didn?t receive any indication that I should be concerned, so I went home since I felt better.   It wasn?t until my friend pointed out that this sounds like anaphylaxis that I thought I should report it. So here I am. Hopefully I?ll be okay.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I understand you need reports on mild side effects as well as serious ones. Mine were uncomfortable, but not alarming. I only had pain in my arm after the first shot, April 2. This report focuses on the second shot, April 30.  Pain in shoulder began about 4 hours after shot. Migraine started about 4 hours and 45 minutes after my shot and lasted nearly three days. Such a long migraine is unusual for me.  However, I avoided taking pain killers as I had heard that could limit immune response to the vaccine, so that could be the reason it lasted so long. Also had some chills and aches and pains.   I am delighted to be vaccinated.  I am reporting here, rather than on your consumer focused reporting site, because it only permits reporting side effects I am experiencing today. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Event happened during  clinic. The patient said "yes" to my question of "is this your 1st dose?", therefore, I vaccinated her with the Pfizer vaccine, acknowledging that this would be her 1st dose of covid vaccine. The patient did not present her vaccine card nor told anyone about her 1st shot. Then, in the process of vaccinating her husband, their son who was sitting right next to the husband but further away from the mom, overheard and mentioned that they actually received the 1st dose of EstraZeneca in India around 50 days ago. This was after the patient was already vaccinated with the Pfizer. The son explained that this happened because the patient did not speak English very well and probably answered my question without fully understanding. Other pharmacists at the clinic including Bahador, who volunteered to be the witness of this event, all heard the son saying that this was because his mom did not speak good English and I clearly verified if this would be her 1st dose.  We did not vaccinate the husband nor the son, and still had the mom who was vaccinated stay 15 minutes. The patient left the clinic after 15 minutes with no adverse events or any complaints.

Patient was a well and active 92 year old man, who walked 2 miles daily with a walker.  He received Covid vaccine dose 1 on 11 Jan.  On or before 30 Jan, he noted pains in one leg while walking.  Newly dilated veins on the lower leg were noted. On feb 2 a doppler US revealed a superficial saphenous vein venous thrombosis, also new onset A flutter. Aspirin begun. On Feb 5 he woke with a cold foot (same side) and was found to have an arterial thrombus from SFA through distal posterial tibial.  He underwent emergency thrombectomy, went to rehab for recovery, on Feb 23 suffered intracranial hemorrhage and died on Mar 10.
OTHER_MEDS: propranolol, other antihypertensive, antacid for GERD
HISTORY: hypertension, GERD, borderline DM, diagnosed while in rehab week before death - well controlled/no Rx.

Patient reported feeling lightheaded status post first dose Pfizer COVID vaccine (Lot: EW0167, expiration date: 08/31/2021) to medic. Medic noted that the client was CAOx4,  her skin was pale, warm and slightly moist, pupils were equal, round, reactive to light and accommodating (PEARRL), respiration rate (RR) was 20. The client's sister stated the client had a history of anxiety and that "she gets this way whenever she gets a shot". Medic walked patient to the zero gravity chair. The client was given water to sip on. At 1213 baseline vitals were taken with client sitting: Blood pressure (BP): 110/82, heartrate (HR): 98, RR: 20, PEARRL. Medic  reports she coached the client on her breathing  to help alleviate her complaint of feeling lightheaded, mild nausea and anxiety. Client reported she felt anxious prior to her vaccination and that her last oral intake was 15 minutes prior to vaccine. Client denied headache, blurry vision and chest pain. At 1220 a second set of vitals were taken while standing: BP 108/80, HR 86, RR 16, CAOx4. Client stated her symptoms were diminishing. Client's RR slowed down to normal rate and rhythm, vital signs were trending to normal and client was negative for orthostatic pressures. Client was advised to stay for additional 30 minute observation. Client's symptoms resolved completely and she was able to ambulate away from observation site without assistance and with a steady gait.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 4 days after the first shot I was feeling very very dizzy.   My ears felt full enough that I thought maybe they were just full of wax.  I bought an over the counter ear cleaning kit.  That didn't relieve any symptoms.  I never get headaches, but a couple days later the front top of my head was throbbing.  The area just above my forehead.  It was not sinus pressure, my face didn't feel any pressure or pain.  My throat also felt like I was being slightly choked.  Not my airway, but just my jugulars.  It began in the evenings.  It would feel like I had been hanging upside down for a while.  My head felt full of blood, like it was going to pop, like my eyes were bugging out.  By a week to 10 days later, my upper arms felt weak, my toes were tingling, and my heart would flutter for just a few seconds occasionally.  I was still dizzy, still felt like I was choking, except I was feeling this way all the time now.  The symptoms only seemed to be staying the same or getting worse.  I have NEVER gone to the doctor on my own in my life to get something checked, but this had me disconcerted enough to check in and see if I should get my second shot at all.  My appointment was to see my doctor was the morning of the same day I was scheduled to get my second Pfizer shot.  My doctor had not heard of these symptoms being associated with the Pfizer shot and chalked my symptoms up to stress.  I am not a stressful person and very much err on the side of "waiting to see what happens" if I feel sick.  I never feel sick.  But I accepted the explanation and took the second shot that day anyway.  It should be noted that the second shot made my left armpit swell up quite a bit.  I did feel dizzy again, but not nearly as much.  The other symptoms seemed to not be as bad either.

The patient has done a telehealth visit with physician  couple hours after the events.  No further treatment was rendered. Treatment information  was not provided. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Skin lesion on right upper extremity; Possible contact transmission of smallpox; This case was obtained on 22APR2021 from the review of scientific literature.    A 27-year-old female presented to health clinic with a 7-day lesion on her right upper extremity. She disclosed that her boyfriend was a marine and was vaccinated against smallpox two weeks prior to her developing the skin lesion. The specific smallpox vaccine that he received is unknown and her boyfriend did not cover the vaccine site as instructed. The patient's skin lesion was non-itchy, approximately 5 millimeter (mm) blister like rash that ulcerated with a grayish, white center and had a surrounding red border. She denied any fever, chills, pets at home, insect bites or trauma to the area. While at the health clinic, the patient's skin lesion was unroofed, and a sample was sent to Laboratory of Public Health for identification. The sample returned positive for Orthopoxvirus DNA by polymerase chain reaction (PCR). The patient was instructed to cover the area while at work, keep the lesion open to air at home, and to avoid skin-to-skin contact. The clinic also reported the event to Department of Health for possible contact transmission of smallpox. The outcomes of the events of possible contact transmission of smallpox and lesion on her right upper extremity was not reported.  The patient's medical history includes asthma. Concomitant medications include unspecified nebulizers for asthma.  Author's Comment: Recipients of smallpox vaccine have a potential for autoinoculation and inoculation of close contacts. Hence, the vaccine recipients should be well educated about proper care of the vaccination site for preventing possible contact transmission of the virus. These include covering the vaccination site, proper hand washing after bandage changes, and avoiding skin-to-skin contact.  Company Comment: The suspected drug as described, was possible ACAM2000. ACAM2000 is a live vaccinia virus that can be transmitted to persons who have close contact with the vaccinee. In this case, the female presented a lesion that was confirmed to be Orthopoxvirus. The lesion is consistent with a contamination due to a secondary transmission from the male who was recently vaccinated; therefore, the lesions are considered related to ACAM2000.  The case is an adverse event of special interest (AESI) and considered medically important for the purpose of submission to the FDA as required commitment.; Sender's Comments: The suspected drug as described, was possible ACAM2000. ACAM2000 is a live vaccinia virus that can be transmitted to persons who have close contact with the vaccinee. In this case, the female presented a lesion that was confirmed to be Orthopoxvirus. The lesion is consistent with a contamination due to a secondary transmission from the male who was recently vaccinated; therefore, the lesions are considered related to ACAM2000.  The case is an adverse event of special interest (AESI) and considered medically important for the purpose of submission to the FDA as required commitment.
